Anonymous Wed 15 Jun 2022 00:53:39 No.48528463 Report
Quoted By:
>>48526995
I haven’t written a lot, but I like to try and deliver exposition in what I call "narrative time".
Exposition dumps have 2 problems which I think you're quite aware of. They break up the action and can be too disconnected from the current scene. I find the best way to solve these is to keep the action while delivering the necessary exposition in short chunks as it happens. That forces you to make your exposition relative to the scene.

The time it takes to read text or say it out aloud is roughly the same. That means the reader's perception of time passing is usually about as quick as they're reading.
Understanding that might help you deliver exposition around dialogue and action more easily. Something in the scene will happen keeping the action going and your character has a moment where they say something to themselves about it before the next thing happens.

When you get it right your writing can be very engaging. Since your readers say things don't feel fleshed out enough you'll probably find yourself expanding scenes as you fit in more exposition. If the action keeps pace you'll probably make your story very rich!

Post how you progress with this. I really hope this advice helps.
